@node "Introduction"
@TITLE "Introduction"
@next "Features"
@prev "Disclaimer"

  @{b}So what is Hurl?@{ub}

  Hurl is a plugin for programs that have a URL grabber (i.e. YAM),
  whereby it extends the capabilities of their built-in URL grabber.

@endnode

@node "Features"
@TITLE "Hurl Features"
@next "Requirements"
@prev "Introduction"

  @{b}So what can Hurl do?@{ub}

  Whenever a URL is double-clicked within, for example, YAM, Hurl will
  either launch your web browser or save the URL to a browser's
  hotlist/bookmark (It will also save to Conatact Manager if available).
  Hurl is able to determine if your system is online and if a web
  browser is available. If not Hurl will save the selected URL to the
  assigned hotlists. Hurl can even allow the user to select what
  actions to perform (saving versus going online), when a network
  connection is not available. 

@endnode

@node "Requirements"
@TITLE "Hurl Requirements"
@next "Installation"
@prev "Features"

  @{b}Requirements:@{ub}

   · Any program that allows "clickable" URLs, such as;
     Yam 2.0
     Thor
     NewsRog
     StrICQ
     mailtext.mcc
     
   · Miami, MiamiDX, Genesis, and/or WinUAE/bsdsocket.library
   · Any, or all, of the web browsers IBrowse, Voyager, and A-Web
   · Contact Manager (Optional)
   · OpenURL library
   · WBStart library
   · MUI

@endnode

@node "Installation"
@TITLE "Hurl Installation"
@next "Usage"
@prev "Requirements"

  @{b}Installation:@{ub}

  Please use the provided Installation script to install Hurl on your system.
  Configuration of Hurl for use with YAM can also be done with the installation
  Script

  Once Hurl is installed you need to have OpenURL properly configured.  Please
  also see the OpenURL documentation of use of its preference program.

  For quick setup of OpenURL's preferences please see the appropriate browser:
  @{"IBrowse" link ibrowse}
  @{"Voyager" link voyager}
  @{"AWeb" link aweb}

  For each web browser set in OpenURL, Hurl will save grabbed URLs to that
  browsers hotlist/bookmark.  If you do not want Hurl to work with certain
  browsers then do not set configure OpenURL prefs for a particular browser.
  (or at least do not set a path to that browser).

  Hurl will also save URLs to Contact Manager, if Hurl detects its presence
  on a user's system.

  @{b}@{u}Manual Installation@{uu}@{ub}
  If you prefer to install Hurl manually then:

     Copy Hurl to "Yam:Rexx/"

  Or any other location.

  @{b}@{u}Configuration of YAM for use with Hurl:@{uu}@{ub}
      · In YAM's @{i}Config->Arexx@{ui}, choose "When Double-Clicking on URL" and set
        options as follows:

         Filetype = AmigaDOS
         File     = "Yam:Rexx/Hurl" OR "YAM:Rexx/Hurl AUTO"
         [] Open Console window   {not selected}
         [] Wait for termination  {not selected}

  @{b}@{u}Configuration of other programs for use with Hurl:@{uu}@{ub}

   @{u}NewsRog:@{uu}

      · Go to NewsRogs @{i}Multimedia->Multimedia Actions@{ui} and set the options as
        follows:

         Media Type = Application/X-URL
         Action     = Send-WWW
         Command    = YAM:Rexx/Hurl OR YAM:Rexx/Hurl AUTO
         Args       = URL ${URL}

         Other Opts
         Input      = NIL:
         Output     = NIL:
         Stack      = 16000
         Pri        = 0
         Dir        = 
         [] Async {not selected}

      · Then in NewsRogs @{i}Config->Filter Options->Glob Display@{ui} enable the URL type.

   @{u}StrICQ:@{uu}

      · Go to StrICQs @{i}Prefs->Notify@{ui} and set the option:

         Go URL    = YAM:Rexx/Hurl %s OR YAM:Rexx/Hurl AUTO %s

   @{u}Thor@{uu}

      · From the menus, select @{i}Settings->Visual Prefs@{ui}

        Set @{i}HTTP command@{ui} to the Hurl program.
        Set cycle-gadget to @{i}Start Program@{ui}.


  @{b}@{u}Command Line Options@{uu}@{ub}
  Hurl supports two optional command line options/arguments:
       1) NOCM
          This will cause Hurl to not save any URLs to CManager, but only to the
          browsers that have been configured in OpenURL's preferences.

       2) CMONLY
          This will make Hurl only save URLs to CManager, and not to any of the
          defined brower hotlists.

  Setting both of these options will result in Hurl never saving URLs to either
  CManager or browser hotlists.

See @{"Tips and Tricks" link "TipsAndTricks"@}

@endnode

@node "Usage"
@TITLE "Hurl Usage"
@next "TipsAndTricks"
@prev "Installation"

  @{b}Usage:@{ub}

  Hurl has two methods of functioning:

 · @{u}AUTO:@{uu} In auto mode, Hurl will save all grabbed URLs to browser hotlists
   when the network is offline.  If online, then the selected URL will be sent to a
   web browser for viewing.

 · @{u}Manual:@{uu} In this mode, Hurl will bring up requesters, asking of the
   selected URL should be saved or if it should connect to the internet for
   viewing.

   When saving URLs, Hurl will bring up a requester containing a string
   requester with the full URL name selected.  At this point you can leave it
   as is, or you can name your URL for saving to the hotlist.

   All URLs saved to the browser hotlists are saved under the group name Hurl,
   therefore keeping them in one easy-to-find area.


  @{u}Using Hurl with Multiple TCP stacks:@{uu}

   If Hurl detects multiple TCP stacks such as Miami, MiamDX or Geneis on the system
   then a requester is presented to the user for selection of the network to connect
   with.

  @{u}Setting the Environment Variables (for advanced users)@{uu}

   When the environment variables are set and detected by Hurl, a new button seletion
   is made available for them

   There are three (3) environment variables that can be set:
      1) HurlCMD
      2) HurlFTPoffline
      3) HurlFTPonline

   To set the variable use the shell command @{i}setvar <var> <cmd>@{ui}.  To save
   it for future useage type @{i}copy env:<var> envarc:@{ui} in a shell window.

   The arguement @{i}<cmd>@{ui} can be any DOS command, and can also be used to execute
   arexx scripts.  To execute an arexx script, preface the script with the @{i}rx@{ui}
   shell command.  An example, using the HurlCMD variable:

        setenv hurlcmd "rx YAM:Rexx/wwwbyemail.rexx %s"

   In the above example the variable @{b}@{i}%s@{ui}@{ub} is set.  This variable informs Hurl to
   pass the URL to the command to execute.  This variable is available for all three
   environment variables.

   The @{i}HurlCMD@{ui} is only available when the network is not available.  Such a
   variable can be usefull for running scripts to fetch web pages by email.

   The @{i}HurlFTPonline@{ui} and @{i}HurlFTPoffline@{ui} are available when Hurl detects
   the URL being an ftp:// type.  This can be usefull if you prefer to save ftp:// to a
   certain file or run a certain ftp client such as ncftp, AmFTP, etc...
@EndNode

@node ibrowse "OpenURL Config for IBrowse"
@next voyager
@prev aweb
In the OpenURL prefs program set the following options
(Please set the path accordingly for your system):

     ---------- Browser Information ----------
           Name: IBrowse
           Path: Internet:IBrowse/IBrowse
     ARexx port  IBROWSE
     Accepts URL as commandline arguement [*]   {selected}

     ------------ ARexx commands -------------
       Show/Uniconify: SHOW
      Screen to front: SCREENTOFRONT
          Open URL...: GOTOURL "%s"
     ...in new window: NEWWINDOW "%s"

@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{uu}@{ub} Please place quatation marks (")
      around the @{b}%s@{ub} variable of OpenURL.


@{"Return to Installation" link Installation}
@endnode

@node voyager "OpenURL Config For Voyager"
@next aweb
@prev ibrowse
In the OpenURL prefs program set the following options
(Please set the path accordingly for your system)

     ---------- Browser Information ----------
           Name: Voyager
           Path: Internet:Voyager/V
     ARexx port  VOYAGER
     Accepts URL as commandline arguement [*]   {selected}

     ------------ ARexx commands -------------
       Show/Uniconify: SHOW
      Screen to front: SCREENTOFRONT
          Open URL...: OPENURL "%s"
     ...in new window: OPENURL "%s" NEWWIN

@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{uu}@{ub} Please place quatation marks (")
      around the @{b}%s@{ub} variable of OpenURL.


@{"Return to Installation" link Installation}
@endnode

@node aweb "OpenURL Config For AWeb"
@next ibrowse
@prev voyager
In the OpenURL prefs program set the following options
(Please set the path accordingly for your system)

     ---------- Browser Information ----------
           Name: AWeb
           Path: Internet:AWeb/AWeb-II
     ARexx port  AWEB
     Accepts URL as commandline arguement [*]   {selected}

     ------------ ARexx commands -------------
       Show/Uniconify: ICONIFY SHOW
      Screen to front: SCREENTOFRONT
          Open URL...: OPEN "%s"
     ...in new window: NEW "%s"

@{b}@{u}NOTE:@{uu}@{ub} Please place quatation marks (")
      around the @{b}%s@{ub} variable of OpenURL.

@{b}@{u}NOTE 2:@{uu}@{ub} Make sure you correctly set the ARexx
        port name to @{b}AWEB@{ub}


@{"Return to Installation" link Installation}
@endnode

@node "TipsAndTricks"
@TITLE "Trouble Shooting"
@next "Author"
@prev "Usage"

  A.K.A. @{b}Embarrassing mistakes you can make when you don't RTFM:@{ub}


  @{i}Hurl Doesn't recognize my browser is running!@{ui}

  For the browsers to be visible to Hurl their Arexx ports need to be
  turned on. For Ibrowse and Voyager this is done in MUI prefs, in the
  System page.

  @{i}Do I single or double-click the URLs?@{ui}

  While Yam needs the URLs to be double-clicked, in both NewsRog and StrICQ
  you only need to single-click them. Hurl won't run two versions of itself
  if you do accidentally double-click on a URL in NewsRog or StrICQ.

  @{i}Why doesn't Hurl bring my Voyager screen to the front!?@{ui}

  It appears that its ARexx port is broken, thus Voyager cannot be commanded to
  pop its screen to the front after a URL is passed to it.  Hopefully the
  author will fix this in the future.

  @{i}Hurl doesn't seem to open my browser.  What gives?@{ui}

  Please make sure that the ARexx port names are correctly defined in the
  OpenURL prefs program.  Also, make certain that the correct path is
  given to the browser in the preference program.

  @{i}Why can't I use Hurl with MicroDotII!?@{ui}

  It appears that the latest version of Microdot (MD) makes use of the
  OpenURL.library to handle its URLs.  It also appears that MD will ignore all
  script settings for URLs if it detects the openurl.library on your system
  (a library that Hurl also uses).  If you want to use Hurl with MD, then
  inform the author of MD to change the way MD works.  Sorry...

  @{i}Hurl does not appear to work with YAM2p7.  Why?@{ui}

  This version of YAM works much like MicrodotII does in the way it makes use
  of the openurl.library. The install script can patch YAM2p7 to correctly
  make use of Hurl.  You can also run the patch program, YamOpenURLpatch, which
  is located in the Hurl archive from a shell window.  Just run the patch
  program, everything is automatic.  Running the patcher a second time will
  restore YAM2p7 to its original state.

  @{i}How do I get Hurl to not save to a certain browser hotlist?@{ui}

  For every browser that is configured in the OpenURL preference program, Hurl
  will save to its hotlist.  To avoid this, delete the entry in the prefs
  program.  If you do not want to delete the entire entry, then just deleting
  the browser path in the configuration is enough to stop Hurl from saving a
  URL to that particular browser's hotlist.

  @{i}I am using MiamiDX, and Hurl doesn't seem to recognize it. All that Hurl
  does is save all my URLs and never lets me view them?@{ui}

  Hurl searches for Miami:MiamiDX to detect if it is available.  Since MiamiDX is
  still in beta, it may have some .exe (.beta, etc.) extension to the program name.
  Deleting this extension, and naming the program to just "MiamiDX" should cure
  the problem.
@endnode

